      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nThe four tables we have studied so far (0, 1, 2 and 3) correspond to numbers that are explicitly represented in the Yupana’s lines, as discussed in previous texts",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1bb0274d-dc51-4740-ac62-4d157b06ad88",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team, Drawing to count",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1bb0274d-dc51-4740-ac62-4d157b06ad88",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team, Yupana (Adition)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "c4c2c00d-7878-42da-9cc4-060cd7f8d225",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team, Yupana (Multiplication)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"yupana0\" class=\"tawapukllay\"><tr><th colspan=\"4\"><i>Yupana</i></th></tr> <tr id=\"tf1\"><td id=\"tc1f1\"><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_up\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_center\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_bottom\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c2_up\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c2_bottom\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc2f1\"><span class=\"dot three_dot_bottom\"></span><span class=\"dot three_dot_up\"></span><span class=\"dot three_dot_center\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc3f1\"><span class=\"dot two_dot_bottom\"></span> <span class=\"dot two_dot_up\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc4f1\"><span class=\"dot dot_center\"></span></td></td></tr></table><p class=\"desc\">Table 1: Representation of a <i>Yupana</i> line according to Poma de Ayala (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8'); return false;\">Prem, Dhavit, <span class=\"htdate\"></span>, pp. 355</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('f5b74f18-0bc4-46d2-8a5c-64dd80b74dd1'); return false;\">Poma de Ayala, Felipe Guaman, <span class=\"htdate\"></span>, pp. 361 - 362</a>). CSS inspired by <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('48dd9187-7ecc-4f54-a387-d9ecc2497de3'); return false;\">W3school</span></a> source code.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In this text, in addition to studying the table of five (5)—which also appears in the Yupana—we will examine the table of four (4). But first, let’s begin with a reflection:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: The Missing Number</b><br /><br />Given the four tables already studied, can you identify any reason why the number four is not explicitly represented in the Yupana’s lines?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_multiple_polygon",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Multiples\n\nWe begin by recalling the general formula used for multiplication tables",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "72dcaa0f-07e3-41de-a637-c5b2f528dc33",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math><mi>r</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>a</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>N</mi> </math></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Formula 1: General multiplication table formula.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "When we worked with values of *a* as one (1), two (2), or three (3), no number other than one (1)—when assigned to *N*—produced a result that matched another table's name. However, this changes with four (4), which is also the product of 2 multiplied by 2.\n\nWhen this occurs, we say a number is a multiple of another; that is, 4 is a multiple of 2",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "5cdee284-576b-4e19-a754-5326002f3598",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "### Quadrilaterals\n\nThere are various geometric figures with four sides. In this text, we will focus on two commonly used quadrilaterals: the square and the rectangle",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "c0c1967a-f27a-4191-82f1-c5e44c44a297",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W., Square",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "3b7542b4-d24a-4708-a890-e2c57fd0f1ae",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W., Rectangle",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"center_notation\"><svg width=\"430\" height=\"130\"> <rect x=\"30\" y=\"0\" width=\"100\" height=\"100\" style=\"fill:lightgreen;stroke-width:3;stroke:none\" /><text x=\"75\" y=\"125\" font-size=\"1.5em\">a</text> <text x=\"140\" y=\"60\" font-size=\"1.5em\">a</text>  <rect x=\"200\" y=\"0\" width=\"200\" height=\"100\" style=\"fill:lightblue;stroke-width:3;stroke:none\" /> <text x=\"410\" y=\"60\" font-size=\"1.5em\">a</text> <text x=\"290\" y=\"125\" font-size=\"1.5em\">b</text></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 1: Representation of a square (left) and a rectangle (right).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "From **Chart 1**, we can draw the following conclusions:\n\n- Both the square and the rectangle are closed geometric figures with four sides.\n- Their sides connect at right angles, similar to the intersection of two sides in a right triangle.\n- The square has all sides equal in length, each measuring *a*.\n- The rectangle, on the other hand, does not have all four sides equal. Instead, it has pairs of equal sides—in this example, one pair has length *a* (like the square), and the other pair has length *b*.\n- The values *a* and *b* can represent any previously studied number, on any scale, which is why they are denoted by letters.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_four",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Multiplying by Four (4)\n\nIn addition to counting the sides of geometric quadrilaterals, the number four is present in various everyday objects, such as chairs, tables, and Indigenous metates—stone tools used to grind food:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"table\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('table', '0%')\" src=\"images/SanJoseCRMuseo/SanJoseCRAntropologia.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 1: Metate exhibited at the Museo Nacional de Antropología, Costa Rica. Photo taken on <htdate0>, during a museum visit.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "10",
                     "day": "17"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "In this figure, it is showing a table in jagar shape. The back of the jagar is plane, allowing the functional usage of the surface.",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Constructing the Multiplication Table of four (4)\n\nTo build the multiplication table for four (4), we apply **Formula 1**, assigning the value four (4) to factor *a*. The results are as follows:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div style=\"border-radius: 30px; margin: auto; border-style= solid; background-color: lightblue; width: 30%; text-align: center\"><b>Multiplication Table of 4</b><br /><br /><math><mi>0</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>4</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>0</mi> </math><br /><math><mi>4</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>4</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>1</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>8</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>8</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>2</mi></math><br /> <math><mi>12</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>4</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>3</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>16</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>4</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>4</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>20</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>4</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>5</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>24</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>4</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>6</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>28</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>4</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>7</mi> </math><br /><math><mi>32</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>4</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>8</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>36</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>4</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>9</mi> </math><br /> <math><mi>40</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>2</mi> <mo>×</mo> <mi>10</mi> </math></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Graphical Representation\n\nWe plot the points from the multiplication table and connect them in a chart:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart1\" class=\"htChart\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 1: Points from the Multiplication Table of 4 connected, forming a straight line. Chart created with <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a>.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "To reinforce the concept of multiples, we compare the tables of two (2) and four (4) on the same chart:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart2\" class=\"htChart\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\">Chart 2: Points from the tables of two and four connected, forming straight lines. Chart created with <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a>.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "Based on what we have studied, we highlight the following from **Chart 2**:\n\n- Except for zero, all results (products) in the four times table are double those in the two times table for the same factor. For example: 20 = 10 × 2, and 40 = (10 × 2) × 2.\n- Some numbers appear in both tables. For example, eight (8) is a multiple of both two and four: 8 = 2 × 4 = 4 × 2.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "latex": null,
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
   ],
   "exercise_v2": [
      {
         "question": "Só existem dois tipos de quadriláteros?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "No",
         "additionalInfo": "Neste texto, nós focamos apenas em quadrados e retângulos, mas há outros tipos de quadriláteros como paralelograma, trapézio, e losango."
      },
      {
         "question": "Quando um número é multiplo de outro, como quatro é multiplo de dois, todos os números que aparecem em uma tabela (quatro) são maiores que valores da outra (dois) pelo mesmo fator (dois)?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "Yes",
         "additionalInfo": "O valor do múltiplo, neste texto o dois, é sempre o valor que separa um valor de uma tabuada da outra. Ou seja, atingimos a tabuada do múltiplo realizando mais uma multiplicação."
      }
